@gpanders Sorry for the churn, but I am going to close this.

I have a working version—and tests, but Vim (and Neovim) already have commands at [`]p`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/change.html#%5Dp) and [`[p`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/change.html#%5Bp). They do something different from unimpaired's commands, but I don't think that they should be hidden by this mapping. (We could map them to something else, but at that point, we're beyond the original idea of bringing over (mostly simple) things people already know from unimpaired.)

Finally, Vim itself (and therefore Neovim) already has *almost exactly* the same thing as unimpaired's "linewise put for charwise (or blockwise) yanks," in [`:put`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/change.html#%3Apu) and `:put!`. Annoyingly, those existing commands don't adjust indentation to the current line. Since other change commands in the same family can adjust indentation to the current line, I am going to propose over at Vim that they add variants for `:put` and `:put!` that handle indentation too. If that happens, Neovim will get those commands for free.
